#: ../../../getting_started.rst:57
msgid "Installation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:59
msgid ""
"Getting Spack is easy.  You can clone it from the `github repository "
"<https://github.com/spack/spack>`_ using this command:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:62
msgid ""
"$ git clone -c feature.manyFiles=true --depth=2 https://github.com/spack/"
"spack.git"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:66
msgid "This will create a directory called ``spack``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:69
msgid ""
"``-c feature.manyFiles=true`` improves git's performance on repositories "
"with 1,000+ files."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:71
msgid ""
"``--depth=2`` prunes the git history to reduce the size of the Spack "
"installation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:77
msgid "Shell support"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:79
msgid ""
"Once you have cloned Spack, we recommend sourcing the appropriate script for "
"your shell:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:82
msgid ""
"# For bash/zsh/sh\n"
"$ . spack/share/spack/setup-env.sh\n"
"\n"
"# For tcsh/csh\n"
"$ source spack/share/spack/setup-env.csh\n"
"\n"
"# For fish\n"
"$ . spack/share/spack/setup-env.fish"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:93
msgid "That's it! You're ready to use Spack."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:95
msgid ""
"Sourcing these files will put the ``spack`` command in your ``PATH``, set up "
"your ``MODULEPATH`` to use Spack's packages, and add other useful shell "
"integration for :ref:`certain commands <packaging-shell-support>`, :ref:"
"`environments <environments>`, and :ref:`modules <modules>`. For ``bash`` "
"and ``zsh``, it also sets up tab completion."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:101
msgid ""
"In order to know which directory to add to your ``MODULEPATH``, these "
"scripts query the ``spack`` command. On shared filesystems, this can be a "
"bit slow, especially if you log in frequently. If you don't use modules, or "
"want to set ``MODULEPATH`` manually instead, you can set the "
"``SPACK_SKIP_MODULES`` environment variable to skip this step and speed up "
"sourcing the file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:107
msgid ""
"If you do not want to use Spack's shell support, you can always just run the "
"``spack`` command directly from ``spack/bin/spack``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:110
msgid ""
"When the ``spack`` command is executed it searches for an appropriate Python "
"interpreter to use, which can be explicitly overridden by setting the "
"``SPACK_PYTHON`` environment variable.  When sourcing the appropriate shell "
"setup script, ``SPACK_PYTHON`` will be set to the interpreter found at "
"sourcing time, ensuring future invocations of the ``spack`` command will "
"continue to use the same consistent python version regardless of changes in "
"the environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:120
msgid "Bootstrapping clingo"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:122
msgid ""
"Spack uses ``clingo`` under the hood to resolve optimal versions and "
"variants of dependencies when installing a package. Since ``clingo`` itself "
"is a binary, Spack has to install it on initial use, which is called "
"bootstrapping."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:126
msgid ""
"Spack provides two ways of bootstrapping ``clingo``: from pre-built binaries "
"(default), or from sources. The fastest way to get started is to bootstrap "
"from pre-built binaries."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:130
msgid ""
"The first time you concretize a spec, Spack will bootstrap automatically:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:132
msgid ""
"$ spack spec zlib\n"
"==> Bootstrapping clingo from pre-built binaries\n"
"==> Fetching https://mirror.spack.io/bootstrap/github-actions/v0.4/"
"build_cache/linux-centos7-x86_64-gcc-10.2.1-clingo-bootstrap-spack-"
"ba5ijauisd3uuixtmactc36vps7yfsrl.spec.json\n"
"==> Fetching https://mirror.spack.io/bootstrap/github-actions/v0.4/"
"build_cache/linux-centos7-x86_64/gcc-10.2.1/clingo-bootstrap-spack/linux-"
"centos7-x86_64-gcc-10.2.1-clingo-bootstrap-spack-"
"ba5ijauisd3uuixtmactc36vps7yfsrl.spack\n"
"==> Installing \"clingo-"
"bootstrap@spack%gcc@10.2.1~docs~ipo+python+static_libstdcpp "
"build_type=Release arch=linux-centos7-x86_64\" from a buildcache\n"
"==> Bootstrapping patchelf from pre-built binaries\n"
"==> Fetching https://mirror.spack.io/bootstrap/github-actions/v0.4/"
"build_cache/linux-centos7-x86_64-gcc-10.2.1-patchelf-0.16.1-"
"p72zyan5wrzuabtmzq7isa5mzyh6ahdp.spec.json\n"
"==> Fetching https://mirror.spack.io/bootstrap/github-actions/v0.4/"
"build_cache/linux-centos7-x86_64/gcc-10.2.1/patchelf-0.16.1/linux-centos7-"
"x86_64-gcc-10.2.1-patchelf-0.16.1-p72zyan5wrzuabtmzq7isa5mzyh6ahdp.spack\n"
"==> Installing \"patchelf@0.16.1%gcc@10.2.1 ldflags=\"-static-libstdc++ -"
"static-libgcc\"  build_system=autotools arch=linux-centos7-x86_64\" from a "
"buildcache\n"
"Input spec\n"
"--------------------------------\n"
"zlib\n"
"\n"
"Concretized\n"
"--------------------------------\n"
"zlib@1.2.13%gcc@9.4.0+optimize+pic+shared build_system=makefile arch=linux-"
"ubuntu20.04-icelake"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:151
msgid ""
"The default bootstrap behavior is to use pre-built binaries. You can verify "
"the active bootstrap repositories with:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:156
msgid ""
"If for security concerns you cannot bootstrap ``clingo`` from pre-built "
"binaries, you have to disable fetching the binaries we generated with Github "
"Actions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:159
msgid ""
"$ spack bootstrap disable github-actions-v0.6\n"
"==> \"github-actions-v0.6\" is now disabled and will not be used for "
"bootstrapping\n"
"$ spack bootstrap disable github-actions-v0.5\n"
"==> \"github-actions-v0.5\" is now disabled and will not be used for "
"bootstrapping"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:166
msgid ""
"You can verify that the new settings are effective with ``spack bootstrap "
"list``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:170
msgid ""
"When bootstrapping from sources, Spack requires a full install of Python "
"including header files (e.g. ``python3-dev`` on Debian), and a compiler with "
"support for C++14 (GCC on Linux, Apple Clang on macOS) and static C++ "
"standard libraries on Linux."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:175
msgid ""
"Spack will build the required software on the first request to concretize a "
"spec:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:177
msgid ""
"$ spack spec zlib\n"
"[+] /usr (external bison-3.0.4-wu5pgjchxzemk5ya2l3ddqug2d7jv6eb)\n"
"[+] /usr (external cmake-3.19.4-a4kmcfzxxy45mzku4ipmj5kdiiz5a57b)\n"
"[+] /usr (external python-3.6.9-x4fou4iqqlh5ydwddx3pvfcwznfrqztv)\n"
"==> Installing re2c-1.2.1-e3x6nxtk3ahgd63ykgy44mpuva6jhtdt\n"
"[ ... ]\n"
"zlib@1.2.11%gcc@10.1.0+optimize+pic+shared arch=linux-ubuntu18.04-broadwell"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:189
msgid "The Bootstrap Store"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:191
msgid ""
"All the tools Spack needs for its own functioning are installed in a "
"separate store, which lives under the ``${HOME}/.spack`` directory. The "
"software installed there can be queried with:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:194
msgid ""
"$ spack -b find\n"
"-- linux-ubuntu18.04-x86_64 / gcc@10.1.0 ------------------------\n"
"clingo-bootstrap@spack  python@3.6.9  re2c@1.2.1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:200
msgid "In case it's needed the bootstrap store can also be cleaned with:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:202
msgid ""
"$ spack clean -b\n"
"==> Removing bootstrapped software and configuration in \"/home/spack/.spack/"
"bootstrap\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:209
msgid "Check Installation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:211
msgid ""
"With Spack installed, you should be able to run some basic Spack commands.  "
"For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:216
msgid ""
"In theory, Spack doesn't need any additional installation; just download and "
"run!  But in real life, additional steps are usually required before Spack "
"can work in a practical sense.  Read on..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:222
msgid "Clean Environment"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:224
msgid ""
"Many packages' installs can be broken by changing environment variables.  "
"For example, a package might pick up the wrong build-time dependencies (most "
"of them not specified) depending on the setting of ``PATH``.  ``GCC`` seems "
"to be particularly vulnerable to these issues."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:229
msgid ""
"Therefore, it is recommended that Spack users run with a *clean "
"environment*, especially for ``PATH``.  Only software that comes with the "
"system, or that you know you wish to use with Spack, should be included.  "
"This procedure will avoid many strange build errors."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:236
msgid "Optional: Alternate Prefix"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:238
msgid ""
"You may want to run Spack out of a prefix other than the git repository you "
"cloned.  The ``spack clone`` command provides this functionality.  To "
"install spack in a new directory, simply type:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:242
msgid "$ spack clone /my/favorite/prefix"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:246
msgid ""
"This will install a new spack script in ``/my/favorite/prefix/bin``, which "
"you can use just like you would the regular spack script.  Each copy of "
"spack installs packages into its own ``$PREFIX/opt`` directory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:256
msgid "Compiler configuration"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:258
msgid ""
"Spack has the ability to build packages with multiple compilers and compiler "
"versions. Compilers can be made available to Spack by specifying them "
"manually in ``compilers.yaml`` or ``packages.yaml``, or automatically by "
"running ``spack compiler find``, but for convenience Spack will "
"automatically detect compilers the first time it needs them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:269
msgid "``spack compilers``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:271
msgid ""
"You can see which compilers are available to Spack by running ``spack "
"compilers`` or ``spack compiler list``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:274
msgid ""
"$ spack compilers\n"
"==> Available compilers\n"
"-- gcc ---------------------------------------------------------\n"
"    gcc@4.9.0  gcc@4.8.0  gcc@4.7.0  gcc@4.6.2  gcc@4.4.7\n"
"    gcc@4.8.2  gcc@4.7.1  gcc@4.6.3  gcc@4.6.1  gcc@4.1.2\n"
"-- intel -------------------------------------------------------\n"
"    intel@15.0.0  intel@14.0.0  intel@13.0.0  intel@12.1.0  intel@10.0\n"
"    intel@14.0.3  intel@13.1.1  intel@12.1.5  intel@12.0.4  intel@9.1\n"
"    intel@14.0.2  intel@13.1.0  intel@12.1.3  intel@11.1\n"
"    intel@14.0.1  intel@13.0.1  intel@12.1.2  intel@10.1\n"
"-- clang -------------------------------------------------------\n"
"    clang@3.4  clang@3.3  clang@3.2  clang@3.1\n"
"-- pgi ---------------------------------------------------------\n"
"    pgi@14.3-0   pgi@13.2-0  pgi@12.1-0   pgi@10.9-0  pgi@8.0-1\n"
"    pgi@13.10-0  pgi@13.1-1  pgi@11.10-0  pgi@10.2-0  pgi@7.1-3\n"
"    pgi@13.6-0   pgi@12.8-0  pgi@11.1-0   pgi@9.0-4   pgi@7.0-6"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:293
msgid ""
"Any of these compilers can be used to build Spack packages.  More on how "
"this is done is in :ref:`sec-specs`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:300
msgid "``spack compiler add``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:302
msgid "An alias for ``spack compiler find``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:308
msgid "``spack compiler find``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:310
msgid ""
"Lists the compilers currently available to Spack. If you do not see a "
"compiler in this list, but you want to use it with Spack, you can simply run "
"``spack compiler find`` with the path to where the compiler is installed.  "
"For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:315
msgid ""
"$ spack compiler find /usr/local/tools/ic-13.0.079\n"
"==> Added 1 new compiler to ~/.spack/linux/compilers.yaml\n"
"    intel@13.0.079"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:321
msgid ""
"Or you can run ``spack compiler find`` with no arguments to force auto-"
"detection.  This is useful if you do not know where compilers are installed, "
"but you know that new compilers have been added to your ``PATH``.  For "
"example, you might load a module, like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:326
msgid ""
"$ module load gcc/4.9.0\n"
"$ spack compiler find\n"
"==> Added 1 new compiler to ~/.spack/linux/compilers.yaml\n"
"    gcc@4.9.0"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:333
msgid ""
"This loads the environment module for gcc-4.9.0 to add it to ``PATH``, and "
"then it adds the compiler to Spack."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:338
msgid ""
"By default, spack does not fill in the ``modules:`` field in the ``compilers."
"yaml`` file.  If you are using a compiler from a module, then you should add "
"this field manually. See the section on :ref:`compilers-requiring-modules`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:347
msgid "``spack compiler info``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:349
msgid ""
"If you want to see specifics on a particular compiler, you can run ``spack "
"compiler info`` on it:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:352
msgid ""
"$ spack compiler info intel@15\n"
"intel@15.0.0:\n"
"  paths:\n"
"    cc  = /usr/local/bin/icc-15.0.090\n"
"    cxx = /usr/local/bin/icpc-15.0.090\n"
"    f77 = /usr/local/bin/ifort-15.0.090\n"
"    fc  = /usr/local/bin/ifort-15.0.090\n"
"  modules = []\n"
"  operating_system = centos6\n"
"..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:365
msgid ""
"This shows which C, C++, and Fortran compilers were detected by Spack. "
"Notice also that we didn't have to be too specific about the version. We "
"just said ``intel@15``, and information about the only matching Intel "
"compiler was displayed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:372
msgid "Manual compiler configuration"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:374
msgid ""
"If auto-detection fails, you can manually configure a compiler by editing "
"your ``~/.spack/<platform>/compilers.yaml`` file.  You can do this by "
"running ``spack config edit compilers``, which will open the file in :ref:"
"`your favorite editor <controlling-the-editor>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:379
msgid "Each compiler configuration in the file looks like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:381
msgid ""
"compilers:\n"
"- compiler:\n"
"    modules: []\n"
"    operating_system: centos6\n"
"    paths:\n"
"      cc: /usr/local/bin/icc-15.0.024-beta\n"
"      cxx: /usr/local/bin/icpc-15.0.024-beta\n"
"      f77: /usr/local/bin/ifort-15.0.024-beta\n"
"      fc: /usr/local/bin/ifort-15.0.024-beta\n"
"    spec: intel@15.0.0"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:394
msgid ""
"For compilers that do not support Fortran (like ``clang``), put ``None`` for "
"``f77`` and ``fc``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:397
msgid ""
"compilers:\n"
"- compiler:\n"
"    modules: []\n"
"    operating_system: centos6\n"
"    paths:\n"
"      cc: /usr/bin/clang\n"
"      cxx: /usr/bin/clang++\n"
"      f77: None\n"
"      fc: None\n"
"    spec: clang@3.3svn"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:410
msgid ""
"Once you save the file, the configured compilers will show up in the list "
"displayed by ``spack compilers``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:413
msgid ""
"You can also add compiler flags to manually configured compilers. These "
"flags should be specified in the ``flags`` section of the compiler "
"specification. The valid flags are ``cflags``, ``cxxflags``, ``fflags``, "
"``cppflags``, ``ldflags``, and ``ldlibs``. For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:418
msgid ""
"compilers:\n"
"- compiler:\n"
"    modules: []\n"
"    operating_system: centos6\n"
"    paths:\n"
"      cc: /usr/bin/gcc\n"
"      cxx: /usr/bin/g++\n"
"      f77: /usr/bin/gfortran\n"
"      fc: /usr/bin/gfortran\n"
"    flags:\n"
"      cflags: -O3 -fPIC\n"
"      cxxflags: -O3 -fPIC\n"
"      cppflags: -O3 -fPIC\n"
"    spec: gcc@4.7.2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:435
msgid ""
"These flags will be treated by spack as if they were entered from the "
"command line each time this compiler is used. The compiler wrappers then "
"inject those flags into the compiler command. Compiler flags entered from "
"the command line will be discussed in more detail in the following section."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:441
msgid ""
"Some compilers also require additional environment configuration. Examples "
"include Intels oneAPI and AMDs AOCC compiler suites, which have custom "
"scripts for loading environment variables and setting paths. These variables "
"should be specified in the ``environment`` section of the compiler "
"specification. The operations available to modify the environment are "
"``set``, ``unset``, ``prepend_path``, ``append_path``, and ``remove_path``. "
"For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:448
msgid ""
"compilers:\n"
"- compiler:\n"
"    modules: []\n"
"    operating_system: centos6\n"
"    paths:\n"
"      cc: /opt/intel/oneapi/compiler/latest/linux/bin/icx\n"
"      cxx: /opt/intel/oneapi/compiler/latest/linux/bin/icpx\n"
"      f77: /opt/intel/oneapi/compiler/latest/linux/bin/ifx\n"
"      fc: /opt/intel/oneapi/compiler/latest/linux/bin/ifx\n"
"    spec: oneapi@latest\n"
"    environment:\n"
"      set:\n"
"        MKL_ROOT: \"/path/to/mkl/root\"\n"
"      unset: # A list of environment variables to unset\n"
"        - CC\n"
"      prepend_path: # Similar for append|remove_path\n"
"        LD_LIBRARY_PATH: /ld/paths/added/by/setvars/sh"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:470
msgid ""
"Spack is in the process of moving compilers from a separate attribute to be "
"handled like all other packages. As part of this process, the ``compilers."
"yaml`` section will eventually be replaced by configuration in the "
"``packages.yaml`` section. This new configuration is now available, although "
"it is not yet the default behavior."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:477
msgid ""
"Compilers can also be configured as external packages in the ``packages."
"yaml`` config file. Any external package for a compiler (e.g. ``gcc`` or "
"``llvm``) will be treated as a configured compiler assuming the paths to the "
"compiler executables are determinable from the prefix."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:483
msgid ""
"If the paths to the compiler executable are not determinable from the "
"prefix, you can add them to the ``extra_attributes`` field. Similarly, all "
"other fields from the compilers config can be added to the "
"``extra_attributes`` field for an external representing a compiler."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:488
msgid ""
"Note that the format for the ``paths`` field in the ``extra_attributes`` "
"section is different than in the ``compilers`` config. For compilers "
"configured as external packages, the section is named ``compilers`` and the "
"dictionary maps language names (``c``, ``cxx``, ``fortran``) to paths, "
"rather than using the names ``cc``, ``fc``, and ``f77``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:495
msgid ""
"packages:\n"
"  gcc:\n"
"    external:\n"
"    - spec: gcc@12.2.0 arch=linux-rhel8-skylake\n"
"      prefix: /usr\n"
"      extra_attributes:\n"
"        environment:\n"
"          set:\n"
"            GCC_ROOT: /usr\n"
"    external:\n"
"    - spec: llvm+clang@15.0.0 arch=linux-rhel8-skylake\n"
"      prefix: /usr\n"
"      extra_attributes:\n"
"        compilers:\n"
"          c: /usr/bin/clang-with-suffix\n"
"          cxx: /usr/bin/clang++-with-extra-info\n"
"          fortran: /usr/bin/gfortran\n"
"        extra_rpaths:\n"
"        - /usr/lib/llvm/"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:519
msgid "Build Your Own Compiler"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:521
msgid ""
"If you are particular about which compiler/version you use, you might wish "
"to have Spack build it for you.  For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:524
msgid "$ spack install gcc@4.9.3"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:528
msgid ""
"Once that has finished, you will need to add it to your ``compilers.yaml`` "
"file.  You can then set Spack to use it by default by adding the following "
"to your ``packages.yaml`` file:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:532
msgid ""
"packages:\n"
"  all:\n"
"    compiler: [gcc@4.9.3]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:542
msgid "Compilers Requiring Modules"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:544
msgid ""
"Many installed compilers will work regardless of the environment they are "
"called with.  However, some installed compilers require ``$LD_LIBRARY_PATH`` "
"or other environment variables to be set in order to run; this is typical "
"for Intel and other proprietary compilers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:549
msgid ""
"In such a case, you should tell Spack which module(s) to load in order to "
"run the chosen compiler (If the compiler does not come with a module file, "
"you might consider making one by hand).  Spack will load this module into "
"the environment ONLY when the compiler is run, and NOT in general for a "
"package's ``install()`` method.  See, for example, this ``compilers.yaml`` "
"file:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:556
msgid ""
"compilers:\n"
"- compiler:\n"
"    modules: [other/comp/gcc-5.3-sp3]\n"
"    operating_system: SuSE11\n"
"    paths:\n"
"      cc: /usr/local/other/SLES11.3/gcc/5.3.0/bin/gcc\n"
"      cxx: /usr/local/other/SLES11.3/gcc/5.3.0/bin/g++\n"
"      f77: /usr/local/other/SLES11.3/gcc/5.3.0/bin/gfortran\n"
"      fc: /usr/local/other/SLES11.3/gcc/5.3.0/bin/gfortran\n"
"    spec: gcc@5.3.0"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:569
msgid ""
"Some compilers require special environment settings to be loaded not just to "
"run, but also to execute the code they build, breaking packages that need to "
"execute code they just compiled.  If it's not possible or practical to use a "
"better compiler, you'll need to ensure that environment settings are "
"preserved for compilers like this (i.e., you'll need to load the module or "
"source the compiler's shell script)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:576
msgid ""
"By default, Spack tries to ensure that builds are reproducible by cleaning "
"the environment before building.  If this interferes with your compiler "
"settings, you CAN use ``spack install --dirty`` as a workaround. Note that "
"this MAY interfere with package builds."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:585
msgid "Licensed Compilers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:587
msgid ""
"Some proprietary compilers require licensing to use.  If you need to use a "
"licensed compiler (eg, PGI), the process is similar to a mix of build your "
"own, plus modules:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:591
msgid ""
"Create a Spack package (if it doesn't exist already) to install your "
"compiler.  Follow instructions on installing :ref:`license`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:594
msgid ""
"Once the compiler is installed, you should be able to test it by using Spack "
"to load the module it just created, and running simple builds (eg: ``cc "
"helloWorld.c && ./a.out``)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:598
msgid "Add the newly-installed compiler to ``compilers.yaml`` as shown above."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:605
msgid "Mixed Toolchains"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:607
msgid ""
"Modern compilers typically come with related compilers for C, C++ and "
"Fortran bundled together.  When possible, results are best if the same "
"compiler is used for all languages."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:611
msgid ""
"In some cases, this is not possible.  For example, starting with macOS El "
"Capitan (10.11), many packages no longer build with GCC, but XCode provides "
"no Fortran compilers.  The user is therefore forced to use a mixed "
"toolchain: XCode-provided Clang for C/C++ and GNU ``gfortran`` for Fortran."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:617
msgid ""
"You need to make sure that Xcode is installed. Run the following command:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:619
msgid "$ xcode-select --install"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:624
msgid ""
"If the Xcode command-line tools are already installed, you will see an error "
"message:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:627
msgid ""
"xcode-select: error: command line tools are already installed, use "
"\"Software Update\" to install updates"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:632
msgid ""
"For most packages, the Xcode command-line tools are sufficient. However, "
"some packages like ``qt`` require the full Xcode suite. You can check to see "
"which you have installed by running:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:636
msgid "$ xcode-select -p"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:641
msgid "If the output is:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:643
msgid "/Applications/Xcode.app/Contents/Developer"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:648
msgid "you already have the full Xcode suite installed. If the output is:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:650
msgid "/Library/Developer/CommandLineTools"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:655
msgid ""
"you only have the command-line tools installed. The full Xcode suite can be "
"installed through the App Store. Make sure you launch the Xcode application "
"and accept the license agreement before using Spack. It may ask you to "
"install additional components. Alternatively, the license can be accepted "
"through the command line:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:661
msgid "$ sudo xcodebuild -license accept"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:666
msgid "Note: the flag is ``-license``, not ``--license``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:668
msgid "Run ``spack compiler find`` to locate Clang."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:670
msgid ""
"There are different ways to get ``gfortran`` on macOS. For example, you can "
"install GCC with Spack (``spack install gcc``), with Homebrew (``brew "
"install gcc``), or from a `DMG installer <https://github.com/fxcoudert/"
"gfortran-for-macOS/releases>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:675
msgid ""
"The only thing left to do is to edit ``~/.spack/darwin/compilers.yaml`` to "
"provide the path to ``gfortran``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:678
msgid ""
"compilers:\n"
"- compiler:\n"
"  # ...\n"
"  paths:\n"
"    cc: /usr/bin/clang\n"
"    cxx: /usr/bin/clang++\n"
"    f77: /path/to/bin/gfortran\n"
"    fc: /path/to/bin/gfortran\n"
"  spec: apple-clang@11.0.0"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:691
msgid ""
"If you used Spack to install GCC, you can get the installation prefix by "
"``spack location -i gcc`` (this will only work if you have a single version "
"of GCC installed). Whereas for Homebrew, GCC is installed in ``/usr/local/"
"Cellar/gcc/x.y.z``. With the DMG installer, the correct path will be ``/usr/"
"local/gfortran``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:699
msgid "Compiler Verification"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:701
msgid ""
"You can verify that your compilers are configured properly by installing a "
"simple package.  For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:704
msgid "$ spack install zlib%gcc@5.3.0"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:713
msgid "Vendor-Specific Compiler Configuration"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:715
msgid ""
"With Spack, things usually \"just work\" with GCC.  Not so for other "
"compilers.  This section provides details on how to get specific compilers "
"working."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:721
msgid "Intel Compilers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:723
msgid ""
"Intel compilers are unusual because a single Intel compiler version can "
"emulate multiple GCC versions.  In order to provide this functionality, the "
"Intel compiler needs GCC to be installed. Therefore, the following steps are "
"necessary to successfully use Intel compilers:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:729
msgid ""
"Install a version of GCC that implements the desired language features "
"(``spack install gcc``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:732
msgid ""
"Tell the Intel compiler how to find that desired GCC.  This may be done in "
"one of two ways:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:735
msgid ""
"\"By default, the compiler determines which version of ``gcc`` or ``g++`` "
"you have installed from the ``PATH`` environment variable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:738
msgid ""
"If you want use a version of ``gcc`` or ``g++`` other than the default "
"version on your system, you need to use either the ``-gcc-name`` or ``-gxx-"
"name`` compiler option to specify the path to the version of ``gcc`` or ``g+"
"+`` that you want to use.\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:743
msgid "`Intel Reference Guide <https://software.intel.com/en-us/node/522750>`_"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:745
msgid ""
"Intel compilers may therefore be configured in one of two ways with Spack: "
"using modules, or using compiler flags."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:750
msgid "Configuration with Modules"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:752
msgid ""
"One can control which GCC is seen by the Intel compiler with modules. A "
"module must be loaded both for the Intel Compiler (so it will run) and GCC "
"(so the compiler can find the intended GCC).  The following configuration in "
"``compilers.yaml`` illustrates this technique:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:757
msgid ""
"compilers:\n"
"- compiler:\n"
"    modules: [gcc-4.9.3, intel-15.0.24]\n"
"    operating_system: centos7\n"
"    paths:\n"
"      cc: /opt/intel-15.0.24/bin/icc-15.0.24-beta\n"
"      cxx: /opt/intel-15.0.24/bin/icpc-15.0.24-beta\n"
"      f77: /opt/intel-15.0.24/bin/ifort-15.0.24-beta\n"
"      fc: /opt/intel-15.0.24/bin/ifort-15.0.24-beta\n"
"    spec: intel@15.0.24.4.9.3"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:773
msgid ""
"The version number on the Intel compiler is a combination of the \"native\" "
"Intel version number and the GNU compiler it is targeting."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:779
msgid "Command Line Configuration"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:781
msgid ""
"One can also control which GCC is seen by the Intel compiler by adding flags "
"to the ``icc`` command:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:784
msgid "Identify the location of the compiler you just installed:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:786
msgid ""
"$ spack location --install-dir gcc\n"
"~/spack/opt/spack/linux-centos7-x86_64/gcc-4.9.3-iy4rw..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:791
msgid "Set up ``compilers.yaml``, for example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:793
msgid ""
"compilers:\n"
"- compiler:\n"
"    modules: [intel-15.0.24]\n"
"    operating_system: centos7\n"
"    paths:\n"
"      cc: /opt/intel-15.0.24/bin/icc-15.0.24-beta\n"
"      cxx: /opt/intel-15.0.24/bin/icpc-15.0.24-beta\n"
"      f77: /opt/intel-15.0.24/bin/ifort-15.0.24-beta\n"
"      fc: /opt/intel-15.0.24/bin/ifort-15.0.24-beta\n"
"    flags:\n"
"      cflags: -gcc-name ~/spack/opt/spack/linux-centos7-x86_64/gcc-4.9.3-"
"iy4rw.../bin/gcc\n"
"      cxxflags: -gxx-name ~/spack/opt/spack/linux-centos7-x86_64/gcc-4.9.3-"
"iy4rw.../bin/g++\n"
"      fflags: -gcc-name ~/spack/opt/spack/linux-centos7-x86_64/gcc-4.9.3-"
"iy4rw.../bin/gcc\n"
"    spec: intel@15.0.24.4.9.3"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:813
msgid "PGI"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:815
msgid ""
"PGI comes with two sets of compilers for C++ and Fortran, distinguishable by "
"their names.  \"Old\" compilers:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:818
msgid ""
"cc:  /soft/pgi/15.10/linux86-64/15.10/bin/pgcc\n"
"cxx: /soft/pgi/15.10/linux86-64/15.10/bin/pgCC\n"
"f77: /soft/pgi/15.10/linux86-64/15.10/bin/pgf77\n"
"fc:  /soft/pgi/15.10/linux86-64/15.10/bin/pgf90"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:825
msgid "\"New\" compilers:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:827
msgid ""
"cc:  /soft/pgi/15.10/linux86-64/15.10/bin/pgcc\n"
"cxx: /soft/pgi/15.10/linux86-64/15.10/bin/pgc++\n"
"f77: /soft/pgi/15.10/linux86-64/15.10/bin/pgfortran\n"
"fc:  /soft/pgi/15.10/linux86-64/15.10/bin/pgfortran"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:834
msgid ""
"Older installations of PGI contains just the old compilers; whereas newer "
"installations contain the old and the new.  The new compiler is considered "
"preferable, as some packages (``hdf``) will not build with the old compiler."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:839
msgid ""
"When auto-detecting a PGI compiler, there are cases where Spack will find "
"the old compilers, when you really want it to find the new compilers.  It is "
"best to check this ``compilers.yaml``; and if the old compilers are being "
"used, change ``pgf77`` and ``pgf90`` to ``pgfortran``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:845
msgid "Other issues:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:847
msgid ""
"There are reports that some packages will not build with PGI, including "
"``libpciaccess`` and ``openssl``.  A workaround is to build these packages "
"with another compiler and then use them as dependencies for PGI-build "
"packages.  For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:852
msgid "$ spack install openmpi%pgi ^libpciaccess%gcc"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:857
msgid ""
"PGI requires a license to use; see :ref:`licensed-compilers` for more "
"information on installation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:862
msgid ""
"It is believed the problem with HDF 4 is that everything is compiled with "
"the ``F77`` compiler, but at some point some Fortran 90 code slipped in "
"there. So compilers that can handle both FORTRAN 77 and Fortran 90 "
"(``gfortran``, ``pgfortran``, etc) are fine.  But compilers specific to one "
"or the other (``pgf77``, ``pgf90``) won't work."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:872
msgid "NAG"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:874
msgid ""
"The Numerical Algorithms Group provides a licensed Fortran compiler. Like "
"Clang, this requires you to set up a :ref:`mixed-toolchains`. It is "
"recommended to use GCC for your C/C++ compilers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:878
msgid ""
"The NAG Fortran compilers are a bit more strict than other compilers, and "
"many packages will fail to install with error messages like:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:881
msgid ""
"Error: mpi_comm_spawn_multiple_f90.f90: Argument 3 to "
"MPI_COMM_SPAWN_MULTIPLE has data type DOUBLE PRECISION in reference from "
"MPI_COMM_SPAWN_MULTIPLEN and CHARACTER in reference from "
"MPI_COMM_SPAWN_MULTIPLEA"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:885
msgid ""
"In order to convince the NAG compiler not to be too picky about calling "
"conventions, you can use ``FFLAGS=-mismatch`` and ``FCFLAGS=-mismatch``. "
"This can be done through the command line:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:889
msgid "$ spack install openmpi fflags=\"-mismatch\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:893
msgid "Or it can be set permanently in your ``compilers.yaml``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:895
msgid ""
"- compiler:\n"
" modules: []\n"
" operating_system: centos6\n"
" paths:\n"
"   cc: /soft/spack/opt/spack/linux-x86_64/gcc-5.3.0/gcc-6.1.0-"
"q2zosj3igepi3pjnqt74bwazmptr5gpj/bin/gcc\n"
"   cxx: /soft/spack/opt/spack/linux-x86_64/gcc-5.3.0/gcc-6.1.0-"
"q2zosj3igepi3pjnqt74bwazmptr5gpj/bin/g++\n"
"   f77: /soft/spack/opt/spack/linux-x86_64/gcc-4.4.7/nag-6.1-"
"jt3h5hwt5myezgqguhfsan52zcskqene/bin/nagfor\n"
"   fc: /soft/spack/opt/spack/linux-x86_64/gcc-4.4.7/nag-6.1-"
"jt3h5hwt5myezgqguhfsan52zcskqene/bin/nagfor\n"
" flags:\n"
"   fflags: -mismatch\n"
" spec: nag@6.1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:912
msgid "System Packages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:914
msgid ""
"Once compilers are configured, one needs to determine which pre-installed "
"system packages, if any, to use in builds.  This is configured in the file "
"``~/.spack/packages.yaml``.  For example, to use an OpenMPI installed in /"
"opt/local, one would use:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:919
msgid ""
"packages:\n"
"    openmpi:\n"
"        externals:\n"
"        - spec: openmpi@1.10.1\n"
"          prefix: /opt/local\n"
"        buildable: False"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:928
msgid ""
"In general, Spack is easier to use and more reliable if it builds all of its "
"own dependencies.  However, there are several packages for which one "
"commonly needs to use system versions:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:934
msgid "MPI"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:936
msgid ""
"On supercomputers, sysadmins have already built MPI versions that take into "
"account the specifics of that computer's hardware.  Unless you know how they "
"were built and can choose the correct Spack variants, you are unlikely to "
"get a working MPI from Spack.  Instead, use an appropriate pre-installed MPI."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:942
msgid ""
"If you choose a pre-installed MPI, you should consider using the pre-"
"installed compiler used to build that MPI; see above on ``compilers.yaml``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:948
msgid "OpenSSL"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:950
msgid ""
"The ``openssl`` package underlies much of modern security in a modern OS; an "
"attacker can easily \"pwn\" any computer on which they can modify SSL. "
"Therefore, any ``openssl`` used on a system should be created in a \"trusted "
"environment\" --- for example, that of the OS vendor."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:955
msgid ""
"OpenSSL is also updated by the OS vendor from time to time, in response to "
"security problems discovered in the wider community.  It is in everyone's "
"best interest to use any newly updated versions as soon as they come out.  "
"Modern Linux installations have standard procedures for security updates "
"without user involvement."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:961
msgid ""
"Spack running at user-level is not a trusted environment, nor do Spack users "
"generally keep up-to-date on the latest security holes in SSL.  For these "
"reasons, a Spack-installed OpenSSL should likely not be trusted."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:965
msgid ""
"As long as the system-provided SSL works, you can use it instead.  One can "
"check if it works by trying to download an ``https://``.  For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:969
msgid ""
"$ curl -O https://github.com/ImageMagick/ImageMagick/archive/7.0.2-7.tar.gz"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:973
msgid ""
"To tell Spack to use the system-supplied OpenSSL, first determine what "
"version you have:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:976
msgid ""
"$ openssl version\n"
"OpenSSL 1.0.2g  1 Mar 2016"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:981
msgid "Then add the following to ``~/.spack/packages.yaml``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:983
msgid ""
"packages:\n"
"    openssl:\n"
"        externals:\n"
"        - spec: openssl@1.0.2g\n"
"          prefix: /usr\n"
"        buildable: False"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:995
msgid "BLAS / LAPACK"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:997
msgid ""
"The recommended way to use system-supplied BLAS / LAPACK packages is to add "
"the following to ``packages.yaml``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1000
msgid ""
"packages:\n"
"    netlib-lapack:\n"
"        externals:\n"
"        - spec: netlib-lapack@3.6.1\n"
"          prefix: /usr\n"
"        buildable: False\n"
"    all:\n"
"        providers:\n"
"            blas: [netlib-lapack]\n"
"            lapack: [netlib-lapack]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1015
msgid ""
"Above we pretend that the system-provided BLAS / LAPACK is ``netlib-lapack`` "
"only because it is the only BLAS / LAPACK provider which use standard names "
"for libraries (as opposed to, for example, ``libopenblas.so``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1019
msgid ""
"Although we specify external package in ``/usr``, Spack is smart enough not "
"to add ``/usr/lib`` to RPATHs, where it could cause unrelated system "
"libraries to be used instead of their Spack equivalents. ``usr/bin`` will be "
"present in PATH, however it will have lower precedence compared to paths "
"from other dependencies. This ensures that binaries in Spack dependencies "
"are preferred over system binaries."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1028 ../../../getting_started.rst:1444
msgid "Git"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1030
msgid ""
"Some Spack packages use ``git`` to download, which might not work on some "
"computers.  For example, the following error was encountered on a Macintosh "
"during ``spack install julia@master``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1034
msgid ""
"==> Cloning git repository:\n"
"  https://github.com/JuliaLang/julia.git\n"
"  on branch master\n"
"Cloning into 'julia'...\n"
"fatal: unable to access 'https://github.com/JuliaLang/julia.git/':\n"
"    SSL certificate problem: unable to get local issuer certificate"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1043
msgid ""
"This problem is related to OpenSSL, and in some cases might be solved by "
"installing a new version of ``git`` and ``openssl``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1046
msgid "Run ``spack install git``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1047
msgid "Add the output of ``spack module tcl loads git`` to your ``.bashrc``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1049
msgid ""
"If this doesn't work, it is also possible to disable checking of SSL "
"certificates by using:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1052
msgid "$ spack --insecure install"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1056
msgid ""
"Using ``--insecure`` makes Spack disable SSL checking when fetching from "
"websites and from git."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1061
msgid ""
"This workaround should be used ONLY as a last resort!  Without SSL "
"certificate verification, spack and git will download from sites you "
"wouldn't normally trust.  The code you download and run may then be "
"compromised!  While this is not a major issue for archives that will be "
"checksummed, it is especially problematic when downloading from name Git "
"branches or tags, which relies entirely on trusting a certificate for "
"security (no verification)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1067
msgid "certificate for security (no verification)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1071
msgid "Utilities Configuration"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1073
msgid ""
"Although Spack does not need installation *per se*, it does rely on other "
"packages to be available on its host system.  If those packages are out of "
"date or missing, then Spack will not work.  Sometimes, an appeal to the "
"system's package manager can fix such problems.  If not, the solution is "
"have Spack install the required packages, and then have Spack use them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1080
msgid ""
"For example, if ``curl`` doesn't work, one could use the following steps to "
"provide Spack a working ``curl``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1083
msgid ""
"$ spack install curl\n"
"$ spack load curl"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1088
msgid "or alternately:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1090
msgid "$ spack module tcl loads curl >>~/.bashrc"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1094
msgid "or if environment modules don't work:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1096
msgid "$ export PATH=`spack location --install-dir curl`/bin:$PATH"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1101
msgid ""
"External commands are used by Spack in two places: within core Spack, and in "
"the package recipes. The bootstrapping procedure for these two cases is "
"somewhat different, and is treated separately below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1107
msgid "Core Spack Utilities"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1109
msgid ""
"Core Spack uses the following packages, mainly to download and unpack source "
"code: ``curl``, ``env``, ``git``, ``go``, ``hg``, ``svn``, ``tar``, "
"``unzip``, ``patch``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1113
msgid ""
"As long as the user's environment is set up to successfully run these "
"programs from outside of Spack, they should work inside of Spack as well.  "
"They can generally be activated as in the ``curl`` example above; or some "
"systems might already have an appropriate hand-built environment module that "
"may be loaded.  Either way works."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1119
msgid "A few notes on specific programs in this list:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1123
msgid "cURL, git, Mercurial, etc."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1125
msgid ""
"Spack depends on cURL to download tarballs, the format that most Spack-"
"installed packages come in.  Your system's cURL should always be able to "
"download unencrypted ``http://``.  However, the cURL on some systems has "
"problems with SSL-enabled ``https://`` URLs, due to outdated / insecure "
"versions of OpenSSL on those systems.  This will prevent Spack from "
"installing any software requiring ``https://`` until a new cURL has been "
"installed, using the technique above."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1135
msgid ""
"remember that if you install ``curl`` via Spack that it may rely on a user-"
"space OpenSSL that is not upgraded regularly.  It may fall out of date "
"faster than your system OpenSSL."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1139
msgid ""
"Some packages use source code control systems as their download method: "
"``git``, ``hg``, ``svn`` and occasionally ``go``.  If you had to install a "
"new ``curl``, then chances are the system-supplied version of these other "
"programs will also not work, because they also rely on OpenSSL. Once "
"``curl`` has been installed, you can similarly install the others."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1148
msgid "Package Utilities"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1150
msgid ""
"Spack may also encounter bootstrapping problems inside a package's "
"``install()`` method.  In this case, Spack will normally be running inside a "
"*sanitized build environment*.  This includes all of the package's "
"dependencies, but none of the environment Spack inherited from the user: if "
"you load a module or modify ``$PATH`` before launching Spack, it will have "
"no effect."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1157
msgid ""
"In this case, you will likely need to use the ``--dirty`` flag when running "
"``spack install``, causing Spack to **not** sanitize the build environment.  "
"You are now responsible for making sure that environment does not do strange "
"things to Spack or its installs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1162
msgid ""
"Another way to get Spack to use its own version of something is to add that "
"something to a package that needs it.  For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1165
msgid "depends_on('binutils', type='build')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1169
msgid ""
"This is considered best practice for some common build dependencies, such as "
"``autotools`` (if the ``autoreconf`` command is needed) and ``cmake`` --- "
"``cmake`` especially, because different packages require a different version "
"of CMake."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1176
msgid "binutils"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1180
msgid ""
"Sometimes, strange error messages can happen while building a package. For "
"example, ``ld`` might crash.  Or one receives a message like:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1183
msgid "ld: final link failed: Nonrepresentable section on output"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1188
msgid "or:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1190
msgid ""
"ld: .../_fftpackmodule.o: unrecognized relocation (0x2a) in section `.text'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1194
msgid ""
"These problems are often caused by an outdated ``binutils`` on your system.  "
"Unlike CMake or Autotools, adding ``depends_on('binutils')`` to every "
"package is not considered a best practice because every package written in C/"
"C++/Fortran would need it.  A potential workaround is to load a recent "
"``binutils`` into your environment and use the ``--dirty`` flag."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1203
msgid "GPG Signing"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1209
msgid "``spack gpg``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1211
msgid ""
"Spack has support for signing and verifying packages using GPG keys. A "
"separate keyring is used for Spack, so any keys available in the user's home "
"directory are not used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1217
msgid "``spack gpg init``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1219
msgid ""
"When Spack is first installed, its keyring is empty. Keys stored in :file:"
"`var/spack/gpg` are the default keys for a Spack installation. These keys "
"may be imported by running ``spack gpg init``. This will import the default "
"keys into the keyring as trusted keys."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1226
msgid "Trusting keys"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1228
msgid ""
"Additional keys may be added to the keyring using ``spack gpg trust "
"<keyfile>``. Once a key is trusted, packages signed by the owner of they key "
"may be installed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1234
msgid "Creating keys"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1236
msgid ""
"You may also create your own key so that you may sign your own packages "
"using ``spack gpg create <name> <email>``. By default, the key has no "
"expiration, but it may be set with the ``--expires <date>`` flag (see the "
"``gnupg2`` documentation for accepted date formats). It is also recommended "
"to add a comment as to the use of the key using the ``--comment <comment>`` "
"flag. The public half of the key can also be exported for sharing with "
"others so that they may use packages you have signed using the ``--export "
"<keyfile>`` flag. Secret keys may also be later exported using the ``spack "
"gpg export <location> [<key>...]`` command."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1248
msgid "Key creation speed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1249
msgid ""
"The creation of a new GPG key requires generating a lot of random numbers. "
"Depending on the entropy produced on your system, the entire process may "
"take a long time (*even appearing to hang*). Virtual machines and cloud "
"instances are particularly likely to display this behavior."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1254
msgid ""
"To speed it up you may install tools like ``rngd``, which is usually "
"available as a package in the host OS.  On e.g. an Ubuntu machine you need "
"to give the following commands:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1258
msgid ""
"$ sudo apt-get install rng-tools\n"
"$ sudo rngd -r /dev/urandom"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1263
msgid "before generating the keys."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1265
msgid ""
"Another alternative is ``haveged``, which can be installed on RHEL/CentOS "
"machines as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1268
msgid ""
"$ sudo yum install haveged\n"
"$ sudo chkconfig haveged on"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1273
msgid ""
"`This Digital Ocean tutorial <https://www.digitalocean.com/community/"
"tutorials/how-to-setup-additional-entropy-for-cloud-servers-using-haveged>`_ "
"provides a good overview of sources of randomness."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1277
msgid ""
"Here is an example of creating a key. Note that we provide a name for the "
"key first (which we can use to reference the key later) and an email address:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1280
msgid "$ spack gpg create dinosaur dinosaur@thedinosaurthings.com"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1285
msgid "If you want to export the key as you create it:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1288
msgid ""
"$ spack gpg create --export key.pub dinosaur dinosaur@thedinosaurthings.com"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1292
msgid "Or the private key:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1295
msgid ""
"$ spack gpg create --export-secret key.priv dinosaur "
"dinosaur@thedinosaurthings.com"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1300
msgid ""
"You can include both ``--export`` and ``--export-secret``, each with an "
"output file of choice, to export both."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1306
msgid "Listing keys"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1308
msgid ""
"In order to list the keys available in the keyring, the ``spack gpg list`` "
"command will list trusted keys with the ``--trusted`` flag and keys "
"available for signing using ``--signing``. If you would like to remove keys "
"from your keyring, ``spack gpg untrust <keyid>``. Key IDs can be email "
"addresses, names, or (best) fingerprints. Here is an example of listing the "
"key that we just created:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1315
msgid ""
"gpgconf: socketdir is '/run/user/1000/gnupg'\n"
"/home/spackuser/spack/opt/spack/gpg/pubring.kbx\n"
"----------------------------------------------------------\n"
"pub   rsa4096 2021-03-25 [SC]\n"
"      60D2685DAB647AD4DB54125961E09BB6F2A0ADCB\n"
"uid           [ultimate] dinosaur (GPG created for Spack) "
"<dinosaur@thedinosaurthings.com>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1325
msgid ""
"Note that the name \"dinosaur\" can be seen under the uid, which is the "
"unique id. We might need this reference if we want to export or otherwise "
"reference the key."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1331
msgid "Signing and Verifying Packages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1333
msgid ""
"In order to sign a package, ``spack gpg sign <file>`` should be used. By "
"default, the signature will be written to ``<file>.asc``, but that may be "
"changed by using the ``--output <file>`` flag. If there is only one signing "
"key available, it will be used, but if there is more than one, the key to "
"use must be specified using the ``--key <keyid>`` flag. The ``--clearsign`` "
"flag may also be used to create a signed file which contains the contents, "
"but it is not recommended. Signed packages may be verified by using ``spack "
"gpg verify <file>``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1345
msgid "Exporting Keys"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1347
msgid ""
"You likely might want to export a public key, and that looks like this. "
"Let's use the previous example and ask spack to export the key with uid "
"\"dinosaur.\" We will provide an output location (typically a `*.pub` file) "
"and the name of the key."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1352
msgid "$ spack gpg export dinosaur.pub dinosaur"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1356
msgid ""
"You can then look at the created file, `dinosaur.pub`, to see the exported "
"key. If you want to include the private key, then just add `--secret`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1359
msgid "$ spack gpg export --secret dinosaur.priv dinosaur"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1363
msgid "This will write the private key to the file `dinosaur.priv`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1367
msgid ""
"You should be very careful about exporting private keys. You likely would "
"only want to do this in the context of moving your spack installation to a "
"different server, and wanting to preserve keys for a buildcache. If you are "
"unsure about exporting, you can ask your local system administrator or for "
"help on an issue or the Spack slack."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1378
msgid "Spack On Windows"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1380
msgid ""
"Windows support for Spack is currently under development. While this work is "
"still in an early stage, it is currently possible to set up Spack and "
"perform a few operations on Windows.  This section will guide you through "
"the steps needed to install Spack and start running it on a fresh Windows "
"machine."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1386
msgid "Step 1: Install prerequisites"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1388
msgid "To use Spack on Windows, you will need the following packages:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1390
msgid "Required: * Microsoft Visual Studio * Python * Git"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1395
msgid "Optional: * Intel Fortran (needed for some packages)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1400
msgid ""
"Currently MSVC is the only compiler tested for C/C++ projects. Intel OneAPI "
"provides Fortran support."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1404
msgid "Microsoft Visual Studio"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1406
msgid ""
"Microsoft Visual Studio provides the only Windows C/C++ compiler that is "
"currently supported by Spack. Spack additionally requires that the Windows "
"SDK (including WGL) to be installed as part of your visual studio "
"installation as it is required to build many packages from source."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1410
msgid ""
"We require several specific components to be included in the Visual Studio "
"installation. One is the C/C++ toolset, which can be selected as \"Desktop "
"development with C++\" or \"C++ build tools,\" depending on installation "
"type (Professional, Build Tools, etc.)  The other required component is \"C+"
"+ CMake tools for Windows,\" which can be selected from among the optional "
"packages. This provides CMake and Ninja for use during Spack configuration."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1417
msgid ""
"If you already have Visual Studio installed, you can make sure these "
"components are installed by rerunning the installer.  Next to your "
"installation, select \"Modify\" and look at the \"Installation details\" "
"pane on the right."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1423
msgid "Intel Fortran"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1425
msgid ""
"For Fortran-based packages on Windows, we strongly recommend Intel's oneAPI "
"Fortran compilers. The suite is free to download from Intel's website, "
"located at https://software.intel.com/content/www/us/en/develop/tools/oneapi/"
"components/fortran-compiler.html. The executable of choice for Spack will be "
"Intel's Beta Compiler, ifx, which supports the classic compiler's (ifort's) "
"frontend and runtime libraries by using LLVM."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1435
msgid ""
"As Spack is a Python-based package, an installation of Python will be needed "
"to run it. Python 3 can be downloaded and installed from the Windows Store, "
"and will be automatically added to your ``PATH`` in this case."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1440
msgid "Spack currently supports Python versions later than 3.2 inclusive."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1446
msgid ""
"A bash console and GUI can be downloaded from https://git-scm.com/downloads. "
"If you are unfamiliar with Git, there are a myriad of resources online to "
"help guide you through checking out repositories and switching development "
"branches."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1450
msgid ""
"When given the option of adjusting your ``PATH``, choose the ``Git from the "
"command line and also from 3rd-party software`` option. This will "
"automatically update your ``PATH`` variable to include the ``git`` command."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1454
msgid ""
"Spack support on Windows is currently dependent on installing the Git for "
"Windows project as the project providing Git support on Windows. This is "
"additionally the recommended method for installing Git on Windows, a link to "
"which can be found above. Spack requires the utilities vendored by this "
"project."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1457
msgid "utilities vendored by this project."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1461
msgid "Step 2: Install and setup Spack"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1463
msgid ""
"We are now ready to get the Spack environment set up on our machine. We "
"begin by using Git to clone the Spack repo, hosted at https://github.com/"
"spack/spack.git into a desired directory, for our purposes today, called "
"``spack_install``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1467
msgid ""
"In order to install Spack with Windows support, run the following one liner "
"in a Windows CMD prompt."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1470
msgid "git clone https://github.com/spack/spack.git"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1475
msgid ""
"If you chose to install Spack into a directory on Windows that is set up to "
"require Administrative Privileges, Spack will require elevated privileges to "
"run. Administrative Privileges can be denoted either by default such as ``C:"
"\\Program Files``, or aministrator applied administrative restrictions on a "
"directory that spack installs files to such as ``C:\\Users``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1483
msgid "Step 3: Run and configure Spack"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1485
msgid ""
"On Windows, Spack supports both primary native shells, Powershell and the "
"traditional command prompt. To use Spack, pick your favorite shell, and run "
"``bin\\spack_cmd.bat`` or ``share/spack/setup-env.ps1`` (you may need to Run "
"as Administrator) from the top-level spack directory. This will provide a "
"Spack enabled shell. If you receive a warning message that Python is not in "
"your ``PATH`` (which may happen if you installed Python from the website and "
"not the Windows Store) add the location of the Python executable to your "
"``PATH`` now. You can permanently add Python to your ``PATH`` variable by "
"using the ``Edit the system environment variables`` utility in Windows "
"Control Panel."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1493
msgid ""
"To configure Spack, first run the following command inside the Spack console:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1495
msgid "spack compiler find"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1499
msgid ""
"This creates a ``.staging`` directory in our Spack prefix, along with a "
"``windows`` subdirectory containing a ``compilers.yaml`` file. On a fresh "
"Windows install with the above packages installed, this command should only "
"detect Microsoft Visual Studio and the Intel Fortran compiler will be "
"integrated within the first version of MSVC present in the ``compilers."
"yaml`` output."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1505
msgid ""
"Spack provides a default ``config.yaml`` file for Windows that it will use "
"unless overridden. This file is located at "
"``etc\\spack\\defaults\\windows\\config.yaml``. You can read more on how to "
"do this and write your own configuration files in the :ref:`Configuration "
"Files<configuration>` section of our documentation. If you do this, pay "
"particular attention to the ``build_stage`` block of the file as this "
"specifies the directory that will temporarily hold the source code for the "
"packages to be installed. This path name must be sufficiently short for "
"compliance with cmd, otherwise you will see build errors during installation "
"(particularly with CMake) tied to long path names."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1513
msgid ""
"To allow Spack use of external tools and dependencies already on your "
"system, the external pieces of software must be described in the ``packages."
"yaml`` file. There are two methods to populate this file:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1517
msgid ""
"The first and easiest choice is to use Spack to find installation on your "
"system. In the Spack terminal, run the following commands:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1520
msgid ""
"spack external find cmake\n"
"spack external find ninja"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1525
msgid ""
"The ``spack external find <name>`` will find executables on your system with "
"the same name given. The command will store the items found in ``packages."
"yaml`` in the ``.staging\\`` directory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1529
msgid ""
"Assuming that the command found CMake and Ninja executables in the previous "
"step, continue to Step 4. If no executables were found, we may need to "
"manually direct spack towards the CMake and Ninja installations we set up "
"with Visual Studio. Therefore, your ``packages.yaml`` file will look "
"something like this, with possibly slight variants in the paths to CMake and "
"Ninja:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1534
msgid ""
"packages:\n"
"  cmake:\n"
"    externals:\n"
"    - spec: cmake@3.19\n"
"      prefix: 'c:\\Program Files (x86)\\Microsoft Visual "
"Studio\\2019\\Professional\\Common7\\IDE\\CommonExtensions\\Microsoft\\CMake\\CMake'\n"
"    buildable: False\n"
"  ninja:\n"
"    externals:\n"
"    - spec: ninja@1.8.2\n"
"      prefix: 'c:\\Program Files (x86)\\Microsoft Visual "
"Studio\\2019\\Professional\\Common7\\IDE\\CommonExtensions\\Microsoft\\CMake\\Ninja'\n"
"    buildable: False"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1548
msgid ""
"You can also use an separate installation of CMake if you have one and "
"prefer to use it. If you don't have a path to Ninja analogous to the above, "
"then you can obtain it by running the Visual Studio Installer and following "
"the instructions at the start of this section. Also note that .yaml files "
"use spaces for indentation and not tabs, so ensure that this is the case "
"when editing one directly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1555
msgid ""
"Cygwin The use of Cygwin is not officially supported by Spack and is not "
"tested. However Spack will not prevent this, so use if choosing to use Spack "
"with Cygwin, know that no functionality is garunteed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1562
msgid "Step 4: Use Spack"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1564
msgid ""
"Once the configuration is complete, it is time to give the installation a "
"test.  Install a basic package though the Spack console via:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1567
msgid "spack install cpuinfo"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1571
msgid ""
"If in the previous step, you did not have CMake or Ninja installed, running "
"the command above should install both packages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting_started.rst:1573
msgid ""
"Spec Syntax Caveats Windows has a few idiosyncrasies when it comes to the "
